node.text:
This year's #Sandhurst Tom Surdyke Leadership Award winner goes to Cadet Ethan Erickson with The College of Saint Benedict Saint John's University @fightingsaintsbattalion.

The award is named in memory of Cadet Thomas Surdyke who died from injuries sustained while saving the life of a drowning stranger. Surdyke was a member of the Company B4 @b4_buffaloes Sandhurst team his Plebe year.

Congratulations to USMA Black who won the overall competition. The top teams are: 

1. USMA Black @usma_sandhurst 
2. USMA Gold
3. Company F1 @f1.firehouse 
4. University of North Georgia @ungcadets 
5. The College of St. Benedict St. John's University @fightingsaintsbattalion

Class of 2022 Cadet Elizabeth Bradley, Company I-3 @i3_icemen, set a new women’s record for the Indoor Obstacle Course Test Wednesday with an official time of 2:20. This Saturday, September 4, Army Football will represent the 3rd Infantry Division during the Army vs. Georgia State University football game in Atlanta, Georgia.

USMA Class of 2023 Cadet Justin Williams is a prior service cadet who served as a behavior health specialist with the 3rd Brigade Support Battalion, 1st Armored Brigade Combat Team, 3rd Infantry Division, (3BSB, 1HBCT, 3ID) from 2017 to 2018.

“The Marne Express is constantly moving. As soon as I got to my unit we went to the National Training Center in Fort Irwin. My platoon leader, a USMA Class of 2016 grad, really inspired me just by the way he was able to control the room when he briefed. Everyone looked up to him regardless of rank. I told him I also wanted to be a great leader, and he encouraged me to apply to West Point. I was accepted into United States Military Academy Preparatory School and now I am here.”

USMA Class of 2025 Cadet John Mitchell served as an Infantry Mortarman with 3rd Battalion, 67th Armor Regiment, 2nd Armored Brigade Combat Team, 3rd Infantry Division (3-67 AR, 2ABCT, 3ID) from 2018-2020.

“I remember the high op-tempo as soon as I got to 3-67AR as we were preparing for our NTC rotation. Staff Sgt. Leatherwood, an exceptional NCO who cares a lot about the soldiers, inspired me to pursue becoming a leader at West Point by his great example and mentorship. I hope to serve with incredible NCOs like him one day, as I owe essentially all success I experienced at the 3rd Infantry Division to such NCOs.”

#WestPoint #GoArmy #beatgeorgiastate #dutyhonorcountry #USArmy #ROTM #rockofthemarne @3rdinfantrydivision @commandant.usmilitaryacademy @westpointadmissions @dean.usma @GoArmyWestPoint @usarmy @usarec

#Army #Football is Ready to Kick Off Another Year!

The Army Black Knights football team will be wearing the unit patch of the 3rd Infantry Division when they take on Georgia State Football Saturday, September 4 at noon. 

Headquartered at Fort Stewart, GA, the 3rd ID is known as the Rock of the Marne and has one of the most successful combat records of any division in The U.S. Army. Sixty members of the 3rd ID have been awarded the Medal of Honor.

The three white stripes of the insignia are symbolical of the three major operations in which the division participated during World War I. The blue field symbolizes the loyalty of those who placed their lives on the altar of self-sacrifice in defense of the American ideals of liberty and democracy. 

Tune in on ESPNU to watch the game live!

node.text:
Meet Cadet Hannah Blakey, Brigade Executive Officer

Blakey, a Persian and French major from Detroit, Michigan, holds the school record in the 4x400 relay and 400 hurdles for Army Women's Track and Field, volunteers as a Sunday School teacher with the Protestant Sunday School Teachers Club and serves as the Cadet In Charge of the Elevation Initiative. Blakey was introduced to West Point when she attended the Summer Leader Experience (SLE) before her senior year of high school. While the academics and military aspects interested her, it was the camaraderie and visibly strong relationships of the cadet cadre that left an indelible mark and convinced her to choose West Point.
 
“My goal this year is to provide the Corps with the environment and resources they need to succeed and to also enjoy their experiences. If I can set the example and have those I lead push themselves and others to serve the Corps and their unit to the best of their ability, I will have succeeded in my mission. I want to set the expectation for every class that comes, that Brigade Staff is here to enable the Corps to succeed, and that is what will make us all successful.”

node.text:
Meet Cadet Anna Tovkach, Deputy Brigade Commander

Tovkach, an Environmental Engineering major, track athlete, and Chi Alpha Sigma scholar from Gainesville, Florida, chose West Point for a combination of reasons. She knew that a service academy would fit her personality and wanted to be far from home in a way that challenged her to be more independent. When she spoke with West Point cadets, they were brutally honest about the difficulty of training and daily life but emphasized the importance of the relationships they had easily formed here. After three years here, West Point has been challenging and uncomfortable most of the time, but she is proud of the person, athlete, friend, and scholar she has become. 

“I hope to set the example for every cadet by showing that your path here does not have to look like anyone else’s. I want to inspire people around me to be passionate about everything they do and have passion for the success of the people around them. I cannot emphasize enough the importance of the relationships we will form here. It is my goal to embody discipline in the little things, which can add up to greatness and unshakable character.” 

Photos by CDT Ellington Ward, Class of 2022, CMG CIC

@cadetmediagroup @dean.usma @westpointadmissions @goarmytrack @e.w.photo @commandant.usmilitaryacademy @anna.tovkach #WestPoint #USMA #leadership

"What a Crass Mass of Brass and Glass! What a Bold Mold of Rolled Gold. . . .! "

The United States Military Academy began the tradition of college rings in 1835, with the chosen motto, ""Amicitiae Periculique Foedus (Danger Brings Forth Friendship)" engraved on the ring. The small rings were designed to be worn on the pinky finger and had flat crests used to seal wax on letters. 

This year, #USMA2022's unique crest and motto, "For Many Stand the Few" will bond them forever and is a wonderful symbol of character, pride, and unity. #WestPoint #USMA #ClassRing @dean.usma @commandant.usmilitaryacademy @westpointadmissions @usma.dmi @cadetmediagroup 

For more photos of the Class of 2022 Ring Ceremony, please visit West Point Flickr

📸: Cadets Tyler Williams, Stephen Litterini, Kyle Swindler, Eli Wright, Josias Galindo
